				<h3 id=post-380> <span  > <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/12/why-i-sponsor-frontlinesmscredit/" rel=bookmark title="永久链接到我为什么要赞助FrontlineSMS：信用">为什么我赞助FrontlineSMS：信用</a></span> </h3> <span  > <small>张贴在<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">博客</a>于2009年12月22日由东道国<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">职位</a> - <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/12/why-i-sponsor-frontlinesmscredit/#respond" title="评论为什么我赞助FrontlineSMS：信用">成为第一位评论</a></small></span> <div class=entry><p> <span  > 2008年7月，我正坐在易趣领导培训，并要求告诉小组什么启发对我的工作我。</span> <span  >我站起来，并立即开始告诉的马赛部落前，我曾访问过度假时，一个星期的故事。</span> <span  >这些人没有自来水，没有电...他们的传统服饰，美丽的红色和紫色毛毯穿着。</span> <span  >这些飞机支。</span> <span  >他们的鞋是由旧的轮胎。</span> <span  >他们很少或几乎没有现代奢侈品，但他们确实有一台设备...移动电话。</span> </p><p> <span  >当时，我曾驾驶PayPal移动的业务在北美地区近两年来的发展努力和实现，没有理由为什么这些马赛应该无法参与全球经济的任何更长的时间，eBay网站上出售或接受他们的产品从国外汇款使用移动电话。</span> <span  >唯一的限制因素是我们的想象，我们的希望，我们的能力来连接这些点，我们知道如何做到这一点。</span> <span  >就在那一刻，我描绘了理想，我会做到这一点，我将有助于建立的移动支付系统，摆脱那些谁也给那些谁需要钱，让这些人有更长期的财政稳定和连接全球市场。</span> <span  >我会用我曾在过去三年在移动支付和手机银行几年中所获得这样做的知识。</span> <span  >离开贝宝不久，我开始我的咨询实践移动支付<a href="http://www.mpayconnect.com/"target=_blank>，www.mpayconnect.com</a>并一直与客户合作，以实现这一愿景。</span> </p><p> <span  >在此期间，一个朋友告诉我，肯银行推出了给我们发电子邮件。</span> <span  >经过近6个月的网络空间，肯和我沟通，在旧金山开会的人。</span> <span  >当我了解到FrontlineSMS多，我想起了在2000-2003年的开源回去工作，并知道它的破坏力与服务器可用于移动支付使用了。</span> <span  >我问他我怎么能帮助他的基础上推出网上支付平台之上垂直。</span> <span  >他疑惑地看着我说：“你不知道本？”</span> </p><p> <span  >当我听到本里昂和他犯下的近20人的志愿者队伍与前线做短信：信用，我不得不帮助他们把他们的努力推向市场。</span> <span  >本和我在纽约会见了耶鲁俱乐部之一，另一个非洲同事下午。</span> <span  >正如我们在该俱乐部的讨论非洲非正规金融系统坐着，移动支付的权力，和互操作性的需要，我决定捐赠他的努力。</span> </p><p><span  >我们需要像FrontlineSMS和FrontlineSMS组织：信贷，以实现财政列入世界的看法范围。</span> <span  >而不是理由的理由的所有移动支付和互操作性是难以或不可能发生，本和他的团队一直在推动其前进。</span> <span  >他们努力想照顾的人谁最需要的，在一天结束时，是最重要的组成部分考虑各种需要。</span> <span  >我的希望是，我们小的捐赠，将帮助实现这些转移到谁的谁在那些有需要的是金钱远见，让这些人有更长期的财政稳定。</span> </p><p><img class=alignleft src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/mPay.png alt="" /><br /> <span  > <em>梅内克谢Gencer姆佩是连接，并为寻求推出移动支付咨询服务的主要客户。</em></span> <span  > <em>连接姆佩专门提供战略，业务发展和产品规划的援助。</em></span> <span  > <em>在成立之前姆佩连接，梅内克谢领导的PayPal移动商务发展的努力。</em></span> <span  > <em>在此期间，她获得PayPal的第一个移动网络运营商处理</em> ， <em>并展开贝宝发送Sprint的移动钱包钱。</em></span> <span  > <em>在此之前，她跑企业软件网关的产品规划部。</em></span> <span  > <em>连接姆佩FrontlineSMS是第一个正式赞助商：信用。</em></span> </p></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-378> <span  > <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/12/india-i-feel-you/" rel=bookmark title="永久链接到印度，我觉得你。">印度，我觉得你。</a></span> </h3> <span  > <small>张贴在<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">博客</a> 12月<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">员额</a> 12日，由主机2009 - <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/12/india-i-feel-you/#respond" title="印度评论，我觉得你。">成为第一位评论</a></small></span> <div class=entry><p> <span  >在<a href="http://conferences.ted.com/TEDIndia/program/">印度的TED会议</a>是一个伟大的起跳点开始，我需要寻找在印度的研究。</span> <span  >我继续为各地的研究机会月份全国旅游会议结束后，参加会议的人们和在班加罗尔，迈索尔，Ahmedebad，村庄乌代和拉贾斯坦，德里，孟买和卢迪亚纳组织。</span> <span  >我是只打算让我做有助于，从整体上-当然通过我的机构，无论其产品在个人层面上，以及。</span> <span  >在我所有的时间在火车，飞机，汽车和autorickshaws这里的主题和我的旅行宰杀道理：</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>设计贫穷：</strong>印度光开关，楼梯和地板不规则的高度，在视频通信混乱，假冒伪劣的接纳为规范工业设计，完全没有进入设计，任何公共或私人空间，一般在80杂音％的情况太糟糕的用户体验它会给你一个头痛的问题。</span> <span  >更何况噪音污染的每一个角落encouragment印度。</span> <span  >我知道没有一个外人，或内幕真的可以改变印度-事实上，印度文化是不会改变的-我希望它不会。</span> <span  >但是小的变化，提高与印度的设计师正确的教育和教育程度越来越高，从消费者的权利要求的质量和生活经验，可以作出很大的不同，以印度的整体。</span> <span  >摆脱贫困的方法可以设计成这样进行教育。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>反向散居：</strong>许多像我这样的印度人，是在国外长大正在返回印度加入“野生，野生东方”。</span> <span  >特德它觉得好像1人/ 3是来自硅谷和尽管印度与硅谷对流以及技术人才的成立，我很高兴地看到我们这一代是如何使用的社会效益和它设计美好的世界。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>矛盾的空间：</strong>印度是一个巨大的矛盾，印度人的工作和生活在这个矛盾的空间，每天和舒适，在这个空间的平衡。</span> <span  >这将有助于解释有关，有时会发生冲突时，外国公司来印度预期的平稳过渡<a href="http://devdutt.com/">。Devdutt Pattanaik</a>在谈话中介绍这一解释与东方和西方，他们踢得如何在商业和文化差异的根本原因位。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>Jugaad：</strong>找到一个解决方法。</span> <span  > Jugaad的字面意思是安排或解决，而这些均因缺乏资源使用。</span> <span  >印度人亦一直Jugaad，这在本质上是做得不正规的方式，而是操纵一个人的方式，找到绕过回答&#39;漏洞没有&#39;。</span> <span  >印度人不喜欢听或说没有。</span> <span  >有几乎总是从某种意义上说，这是一个伟大的居住心态</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>土著发明：</strong>财政和物质是由最终用户发明的产品更有价值的东西比一个人的，我们设计了他们。</span> <span  >在<a href="http://www.sristi.org/hbnew/">蜜蜂网络</a>和他们的发明和<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chit_fund">节基金</a>是这个伟大的例子。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>破坏性一切：</strong>破坏性的商业模式，破坏性的设计，思考，讨论-这一切，正在接受越来越多的印度和世界的一个更具吸引力的选择比久经考验。</span> <span  >中断不仅源于创新，但更重要的是使公平竞争的民主。</span> <span  >我绝对同意这个主题。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>Philanthrocapitalism：</strong>或者，同情心的业务，我喜欢称呼它，往往是烤成许多印度公司。</span> <span  >文化上，社会责任，是人们日常生活的一部分，因此其大部分在印度事后比其他地方少。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>腐败：</strong>没有一件事已经停止印度的进步不止这些。</span> <span  >之前也做更透明的方式，以及受贿消失，它将会是非常困难的印度将成为世界领袖，应该是。</span> <span  >我希望自己的反腐败斗争的运气<a href="http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/life/2005/08/19/stories/2005081900080200.htm">Shaffi马瑟</a>手。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>孩子们：</strong>据悉，在印度真正的改变，世界将与下一代，在印度的教育需要一场革命，现在。</span> <span  >许多人都这样做，包括基兰塞西的<a href="http://www.schoolriverside.com/">滨江学校</a>和新浪娱乐多希谁带来<a href="0">香格里拉新学校</a>到印度。</span> <span  >随着教育的责任，烤到他们的权利类型，为可持续发展或社会变革或设计思想，它的下一代就是改变生活。</span> <span  >尽管如此，拥有世界上最大，最年轻的经济，可能会变成它的最大实惠是印度最大的批评之一。</span> </p><p><span  > <strong>手机真理：</strong>大家都知道它的重要银行的开设银行账户，建立支付系统。</span> <span  >我看到，在许多地方还没有被用来尚未充分发挥其潜力，如在教育部门，在食品，在广告和公共服务-这可能真的被证明是最好的工具，以解决在印度大规模的问题。</span> </p><p> <span  >多来我的过程和消化这方面的研究难以置信的一个月。</span> </p><p><img class=alignleft src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/team_raina.jpg alt="" /><br /> <span  > <em>这个职位是由雷伊内库姆拉贡献，交通银行主任FrontlineSMS：信用。</em></span> </p><p> <span  > <em>要联系雷伊内，电子邮件</em></span> <em><br /></em> <span  > <a href=mailto:raina@credit.frontlinesms.com><em>raina@credit.frontlinesms.com。</em></a></span> </p></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-376> <span  > <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/12/the-hidden-side-of-cash/" rel=bookmark title="永久连结现金隐藏的一面">在现金隐藏的一面</a></span> </h3> <span  > <small>张贴在<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">博客</a>于2009年12月7日由东道国<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">职位</a> - <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/12/the-hidden-side-of-cash/#respond" title="评论现金隐藏的一面">成为第一位评论</a></small></span> <div class=entry><p> <span  >想象一下，明天醒来发现每你拥有流动性资产已由1美元的法案取代的价值。</span> <span  >这与500美元限额的信用卡？</span> <span  >它只是爆裂500 $ 1秒你的钱包的接缝。</span> <span  >您的$ 30,000退休帐户？</span> <span  >祝你好运，即使发现根据该现金山区桌面。</span> <span  >但在此之前落户的研究计算出来，你可能要锁定后门，因为我不会把它过去的邻居，以帮助自己的钱数一把。</span> <span  > （毕竟，盗窃现金是很容易，打击别人的网上银行帐户。）财务管理公司在这个世界上新的和惊人文字的扭曲。</span> </p><p> <span  >事实上，如果你碰巧住在金沙萨，刚果，出现上述情况的民主共和国首都将是一个drearily熟悉的场景，而不是一个有趣的思想实验。</span> <span  >最正式的金融服务，如储蓄，支票，信用卡，几乎不存在在刚果民主共和国，并在当地货币最大的法案是500法郎的钞票-价值约在编写时0.55。</span> <span  >对于典型的刚果商人-说，一名女子卖150法郎（约合0.17美元）的杯子在Makala木薯面粉市场-一个很好的一天的销售额将意味着相当不方便的法郎桩携带。</span> <span  >另一种方法是付出代价转化为美国的美元，刚果民主共和国的非官方的第二大货币，它具有较高的教派和较低的通货膨胀率来的法郎-并留下一一点，结果较差。</span> </p><p> <span  >尽管与小土堆处理法案明显的麻烦，但是，它甚至可以说是最严重的问题，刚果民主共和国的现金只有经济提出的问题。</span> <span  >当我在采访小额信贷客户在金沙萨今年早些时候，我印象最深的是一些人说，他们谁的现金被盗-无论是在街上，在他们的家园，甚至未来的小额信贷银行凭借其新出获得贷款资金捆绑到他们的pagnes角落整齐，和等待，以满足他们的聪明的小偷。</span> <span  >这是现金隐藏的一面，留下一个本已脆弱的穷人更容易受到盗窃，少能够进行私下的任何类型的金融交易。</span> <span  >这就是为什么，如果小额金融业真正致力于为穷人服务，它需要的现金后离开，拥抱移动银行。</span> </p><p><span  >在刚果民主共和国的国家一样，移动小额信贷很可能提供的第一和唯一的机会，大多数人要进行金融交易，方便，私人和安全的-在已为几十年来在西方理所当然的交易类型。</span> <span  >这个从现金转换的影响，移动真的不为过。</span> <span  >毕竟，如果你愿意是-从方便管理您的笔记本电脑或移动电话，或站立超过1美元的法案后卫组成您一生的积蓄，现在在你（新磊）床垫填充您的银行帐户？</span> </p><p> <span  >我是这么想的。</span> </p><p><img class=alignleft src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/team_rachel.jpg alt="" /><br /> <span  > <em>这个职位是雷切尔斯特罗姆作出了贡献，撒哈拉以南非洲地区协调员FrontlineSMS：信用。</em></span> </p><p> <span  > <em>要联系雷切尔，电子邮件</em></span> <em><br /></em> <span  > <a href=mailto:rachel@credit.frontlinesms.com><em>rachel@credit.frontlinesms.com。</em></a></span> </p></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-358> <span  > <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/12/microloans-in-rural-areas-through-mobile-phones/" rel=bookmark title="永久链接到农村七千五百万通过手机">在农村地区通过手机七千五百万</a></span> </h3> <span  > <small>张贴在<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">博客</a>于09年12月3日由东道国<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">员额</a> - <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/12/microloans-in-rural-areas-through-mobile-phones/#comments" title="评论在农村地区通过手机七千五百万">1条评论</a></small></span> <div class=entry><p> <span  >不久，拉丁美洲和加勒比地区（LAC）的农村居民将获得意外的对小额贷款，储蓄和保险... ...，并通过他们的移动电话。</span> <span  >这表明在（MFI）的小额信贷机构的趋势，越来越先进的移动支付系统及开放源码程序，作为两者之间的桥梁的出现。</span> </p><p> <span  >这个职位将简要地解释小额信贷机构和工作的移动支付，开放源码软件如何能够促进经济融合和什么样的挑战面对这一进程。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>导言</strong></span> </p><p><img class=alignleft src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/jorge_post_1.jpg alt="" /> <span  >据世界银行，只有35％的拉丁美洲和加勒比的人口获得金融服务。</span> <span  >这这样的情况，减少了支付，储蓄和信贷的选择和限制他们的融资渠道的低效率和更加昂贵。</span> </p><p> <span  >获得储蓄，信贷，保险和其他金融服务是必要的，以改善你的立场和克服不可预见的紧急金融情况（医疗费，教育收费，偶尔失业...）。</span> <span  >此外，适当的财务规划，使家庭和企业家，以提高其业务成长的机会，减少收入的波动（即消费平滑），凝聚人的储蓄和财产，并最终提高他们的能力，应对经济冲击。</span> </p><p> <span  >最近的研究表明，库存的个人和家庭经济条件较佳谁比那些缺乏获得正规的金融服务。</span> <span  >在某种程度上，收入和储蓄增加，库存的个人抵御金融危机，可以从简单的日常生存到中期和长期规划。</span> </p><p> <span  >这些情况是特别重要的是在农村地区，欠发达地区和城市，一般来说在非正规部门，只能由手机访问控制这些地方。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>小额信贷机构</strong></span> </p><p><img class=alignright src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/jorge_post_2.jpg alt="" /> <span  >小额信贷和融资来上升20世纪70年代，当社会企业家开始提供小额贷款和其他金融服务，谁没有来由于缺乏担保的正式访问的财政穷人企业家。</span> </p><p> <span  >拉丁美洲和加勒比一些贫穷国家的小额信贷发展的先锋。</span> <span  >这方面一直没有停止发展，已经达到这样的程度<a href="http://idbdocs.iadb.org/wsdocs/getdocument.aspx?docnum=2189221">，2009年全球显微镜</a>研究是由著名的财经刊物经济学家上市秘鲁，玻利维亚，准备，厄瓜多尔和哥伦比亚（顺序）的前十位国家与世界更好的营商小额信贷环境。</span> </p><p><span  >大多数小额信贷机构开始作为非政府非营利组织（非政府组织），农村银行或其他金融合作社，或国家开发银行。</span> <span  >随着时间的推移，对小额信贷机构的许多人成为非营利性机构，因为这是一个许可证和提供储蓄服务的需求。</span> <span  >以营利为目的小额信贷机构可以归到非银行金融机构，商业银行或专门从事小额信贷的银行，提供各类服务财政部门。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>移动支付</strong></span> </p><p> <span  >移动支付是一个系统，允许用户存入移动钱包的钱和分配通过短信（SMS）它。</span> <span  >移动支付更快，更便宜比将钱存入银行，邮局或长途巴士司机。</span> <span  >通过使用这种付款类型，农村人可以放弃前往银行或邮局，以获取资金和转让，因此，可以投入更多的时间来生产活动。</span> </p><p> <span  >移动支付也是一个途径是实行财政剥夺权力社区正规的金融服务。</span> </p><p> <span  >移动支付的先锋，如小额贷款，是在贫穷国家的企业家，谁认识到，他们可以透过出售服务的经济金字塔（国际收支）基础货币。</span> <span  >有两个原因：这个市场的规模和人口之间的流动电话渗透率率高的原因。</span> </p><p> <span  > <a href="http://www.safaricom.co.ke/index.php?id=745">Safaricom公司的M - PESA（</a>肯尼亚）， <a href="http://smart.com.ph/">智能货币</a> （菲律宾）， <a href="http://web.globe.com.ph/">环球集团现金</a> （菲律宾）是其中的先驱者。</span> <span  >智能理财＆G公司现金单独带来大约二万七千五点零零万每月菲律宾美元！</span> <span  >若要了解更多关于如何典型的移动支付系统的运作方式，请参阅<a href="http://www.splash-cash.com/pdf/using-splash.pdf">现金飞溅</a> （塞拉利昂）， <a href="http://www.obopay.co.in/mobile_obopay.html">将Obopay（</a>印度）和<a href="http://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=p/gen/mobile-outside">贝宝</a> （美国）的信息。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>如何开放源码软件促进金融包容性</strong></span> </p><p><img class=alignleft src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/jorge_post_3.jpg alt="" /> <span  >看看下面的例子：一个需要钱的农民在市场租一个摊位出售其产品。</span> <span  >目前，他也没有其他办法得到它。</span> <span  >最有可能的，他便要到最近的MFI和申请微型（与信用贷款利率可以达到28％左右，根据<a href="http://www.cgap.org/">咨询小组</a> ， <a href="http://www.cgap.org/">协助穷人</a> ）。</span> <span  >他需要长途跋涉的小额信贷机构支付每周偿还贷款。</span> </p><p> <span  >随着移动支付系统，在我们的例子农民应该能够避免费时（过境时间）和金钱（运输成本获得贷款），通过他的手机的机会成本。</span> <span  >从理论上说，这种交易应该很简单。</span> </p><p> <span  >但在实践中，小额信贷机构提供有困难的，甚至在非洲和亚洲国家有移动支付渠道等服务。</span> <span  >为什么？</span> <span  >小额信贷机构缺乏一种软件无缝集成与管理信息系统，移动支付。</span> </p><p> <span  >与处理支付能力将有助于解决上述问题，发展自由和开放源码软件。</span> <span  >这个软件将提供一个在移动支付系统和小额信贷机构的桥梁，使小额信贷机构使用移动支付的款项分发给群众，自动生成客户信用记录，维持充裕的审计路径。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>挑战</strong></span> </p><p>Frontlinesms:Credit is an initiative that aims to bring formal financial services to  rural and disconnected populations via simple text message (SMS). By merging free and open source software like <a href="http://www.frontlinesms.com/">Frontlinesms</a> , which turns a computer into a mass-SMS communication hub, with the ability to process prominent mobile payment systems and integrate with common microfinance management systems, FrontlineSMS:Credit will facilitate financial inclusion in LAC. </p><p> The task that FrontlineSMS:Credit faces is not easy. On one side are the regulatory environments that enable mobile phone use as a tool for financial inclusion. While some countries are well advanced in the field, specifically Peru and Mexico (see <a href="http://movilybanca.afi.es/2009/09/09/america-latina-en-contexto-entorno-para-los-servicios-financieros-moviles/">América Latina en contexto: el entorno para los servicios financieros móviles</a> ), governments in LAC are still far away from creating enabling environments. </p><p> On the other hand is the development of mobile payment systems in the region. Fortunately, several systems have already emerged: <a href="http://www.tigocash.com.py/">Tigo Cash</a> in Paraguay, <a href="http://www.arturogoga.com/2009/05/20/se-lanza-en-per-el-modelo-de-pagos-por-celular/">Pago Móvil</a> in Perú, <a href="http://nipper.com.mx/">Nipper</a> in México and <a href="http://www.novaoi.com.br/">Oi Paggo</a> in Brazil are a few. </p><p> And do not forget also the distribution networks, interoperability of mobile payment systems, marketing, security of transactions, customer trust, the accessibility of mobile phone platforms, transparency, etc.. </p><p> FrontlineSMS: Credit has been working since October to produce a range of open source tools to expand the functionality of mobile payments. One of its modules will be ready for field testing and free download by the Spring, whether in Africa or Asia, where as we saw, mobile payment systems are well developed. In LAC we have it in early 2011, or earlier if circumstances permit. </p><p> The short history of development is fraught with false promises and failed benchmarks, says Ben Lyon, Executive Director of FrontlineSMS: Credit, and neither mobile payments nor microfinance should be exalted as the next &#39;silver bullet.&#39; Nevertheless, the rapid emergence of mobile payment systems across the developing world presents a tremendous and exciting opportunity for billions of people… we must seize this opportunity! </p><p> <strong>[ <a href="http://textosms.wordpress.com/2009/12/03/microprestamos-en-zonas-rurales-a-traves-de-telefonos-moviles/"target=_blank>Read this post in Spanish at Jorge&#39;s blog</a> ]</strong> </p><p><img class=alignleft src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/team_jorge.jpg alt="" /><br /> <em>This post was contributed by Jorge L. Alonso G., Central &amp; South America Regional Coordinator for FrontlineSMS:Credit.</em> </p><p> <em>To contact Jorge, email <br /> <a href=mailto:jorge@credit.frontlinesms.com>jorge@credit.frontlinesms.com</a> .</em> </p><h5> <span  > ____________________</span> <br /> <em>Sources Consulted:</em> <br /> 1. <a href="http://www.fundacionandares.org/">Fundación para el Desarrollo de las Microfinanzas, Andares</a> <br /> 2. <a href="http://microrate.com/es/home/about-microfinance/general-information-on-microfinance">MicroRate: The Rating Agency for Microfinance</a> <br /> 3. <a href="http://movilybanca.afi.es/">Telefonía Móvil y Acceso a Servicios Financieros en América Latina y Caribe</a> </h5></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-346> <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/11/ict4d-mission-drift-waste/" rel=bookmark title="Permanent Link to ICT4D, Mission Drift &amp; Waste">ICT4D, Mission Drift &amp; Waste</a> </h3> <small>Posted in <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">Blog posts</a> on November 30th, 2009  by Ben Lyon – <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/11/ict4d-mission-drift-waste/#respond" title="Comment on ICT4D, Mission Drift &amp; Waste">Be the first to comment</a></small> <div class=entry><p><span  >信息通信技术促进发展，或ICT4D，是在发展空间越来越热门的话题。</span> For better or worse, it may even be turning into the next fad – the default response to a world of unique challenges and circumstances. If sixty years of development history suggest anything, it is that mission drift and waste are the likely byproducts of hype, an outcome which neither beneficiaries nor practitioners of ICT4D can afford. In order to avoid such an outcome, the ICT4D community must accept its growing fame with humility, caution, patience, and self-scrutiny. </p><p> <strong>Humility</strong> </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/ict4d_post_01.jpg class=alignright> Most fundamentally, we have to acknowledge that technology is a not a solution, but rather one tool in the toolkit. Whatever solutions result from technology are largely a consequence of user uptake and ingenuity. End users leveraged mobile technology, for instance, to create the airtime transfer and &#39;flash&#39;, much like Twitter users, not only created the @ reply and hash tag, but altered its very purpose from “What are you doing?” to “Share and discover what&#39;s happening right now, anywhere in the world”. That more than 1/3 of M-PESA clients in Kenya hold informal savings in their &#39;mobile wallet&#39; and that Iranians used Twitter to compel coverage by the mainstream media (remember #CNNfail?) is further proof. Technology providers are facilitators, not White Knights. </p><p> <span  > <strong>注意</strong></span> </p><p> As with development in general, this isn&#39;ta game. Real lives and livelihoods are on the line and mistakes can have dire consequences. Technologies must therefore be accessible, affordable, durable and intuitive. Without foresight and commitment to long-run sustainability, providers may be creating user bases only to rip the floor out from underneath them when the business model fails. By way of example, imagine how millions of Filipinos would be impacted if either SMART Money or GCASH went under. </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/ict4d_post_02.jpg class=alignleft> <strong>Patience</strong> </p><p> In the world of semi-conductors and fiber optics, it&#39;s difficult to imagine progress in non-exponential terms. In the developing world, however,  Murphy and Maslow are far more relevant than Moore. Despite incredible bursts of growth – leapfrogging – in telecommunications and gradual gains in internet penetration, a tremendous amount of work remains unfinished. Consequently, some technologies are more appropriate than others insofar as they respond to current market failures and user needs. Cloud computing and Android, for example, will dramatically alter the development landscape in the future, but remain largely inappropriate in the present. ICT4D practitioners should therefore be driven by &#39;pull&#39; instead of attempting to &#39;push&#39; the &#39;next big thing&#39;. More simply, supply is driven by demand, not vice versa. </p><p> <strong>Self-Scrutiny</strong> </p><p> Everyone comes to the table with pride and predispositions, especially in development. One of the biggest assets of the ICT industry  is its focus on engineering, a science driven by the simple question: How do I make process X more efficient? Once we add “4D” to the equation, however, we introduce a host of conflicting ideologies and practices that shift the focus from quantitative to qualitative. As ICT4D continues to grow, we must constantly ask ourselves: What biases and blinders are we bringing to the table? </p><p> <strong>In Closing…</strong> </p><p> We cannot let ICT4D become a victim of its own success. In order to help mitigate the varied challenges and circumstances in our areas of operation, it is critical that we constantly revisit the following four questions: </p><ol><li> How are we facilitating organic solutions to local problems? </li><li> How will the user be impacted if we fail? </li><li> Are we basing our strategy on push or pull? </li><li> Are we driven by efficiency or ego? </li></ol><p></p><hr /><span  > <strong>阿育王：</strong> <em>创新的公共承载在海得拉巴，印度，在2010年2月技术协会4，会议探讨的技术，发明和社会变革。</em></span> <span  > <em>了解有关这次会议的更多信息<a href="http://tech.ashoka.org/"target=_blank>：http://tech.ashoka.org。</a></em></span> <span  > <em>这个博客帖子是在其竞争进入官方博客找到旅行和采访。</em></span> </p></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-337> <span  > <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/11/microsave-3rd-generation-microfinance/" rel=bookmark title="永久链接到微额和第三代小额信贷">微额与第三代小额信贷</a></span> </h3> <span  > <small>张贴在<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">博客</a>于2009年11月21日由东道国<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">职位</a> - <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/11/microsave-3rd-generation-microfinance/#respond" title="在微额和第三代评论小额信贷">成为第一位评论</a></small></span> <div class=entry><p> <span  >在非洲开始于1998年，微<a href="http://www.microsave.org/">（www.MicroSave.org）</a>现在是一个近80经验丰富的专业团队已经运作了十多年的，并且经常受到客户的描述为“金融服务供应商最可信赖的咨询公司”。</span> <span  >在内罗毕，坎帕拉，勒克瑙，海得拉巴，微工程办公室在亚洲和非洲将一份关于在商业中心的客户强烈关注，并制造产品和运载系统的客户端响应或“市场主导”。</span> </p><p> <span  >微额特别是众所周知的实地层次的研究，这需要与穷人广泛的访问（包括小额信贷客户），以便更好地了解他们的财务行为和风险状况。</span> <span  >微额的行动研究小额信贷机构，以更好地协助听取客户和设计更好的市场信息为基础适当的金融产品。</span> <span  >这两个研究活动是相辅相成的，直接反馈到工具箱/课程开发和传播工作。</span> </p><p> The combined experience of its core research and close work with a wide variety of partners in Asia and Africa has allowed MicroSave to develop and test a series of practice-based and practitioner-focused, training curricula and workshops – its “toolkits”. MicroSave uses a structured approach based on its internationally acclaimed toolkits to deliver its services to clients. These toolkits have been widely acclaimed, and have been translated into over 20 different languages. MicroSave toolkits are now used across the globe. The toolkit-based approach ensures a step-by-step process for field assignments, which yields consistency and unparalleled quality. </p><p> For more see <a href="http://www.microsave.org/static/content/microsave-history">MicroSave History</a> </p><p> For several years now, MicroSave has been closely involved with several e- and m-banking initiatives in Africa and Asia, in particular working on the “soft side” of e/m-banking where the technology interfaces with the customer. Thus MicroSave has worked closely with a variety of providers including Vodafone&#39;s M-Pesa, Kenya Post Office Savings Bank&#39;s Cash Xpress and Eko-Airtel-State Bank of India, Drishtee – HDFC Bank, mChek and many others to provide support/conduct market research, process mapping and analysis, pilot-testing, customer interface and satisfaction, channel development, brand/marketing and financial education etc. In addition, MicroSave holds annual “M-banking Dialogues”, to bring together a select group of providers that are actually implementing m-banking solutions. The Dialogues allow practitioners to discuss some of the nitty-gritty details and challenges involved with developing, testing and rolling out e/m-banking solutions. The Dialogues have proved immensely valuable for participants, who leave with significant learning through the peer-to-peer exchanges. For more on our experience with or findings on m-banking, see <a href="http://www.microsave.org/mobile_banking">http://www.microsave.org/mobile_banking</a> . </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/microsave_post_03.jpg></p><p> <strong>Describe the microfinance ecosystem in India? Do any challenges stand out?</strong> </p><p> Microfinance in India has evolved over the past two decades since its inception in early 1990s. The SHG-bank linkage model, its first prototype, was an offspring from an unlikely marriage between the social intermediation role of the civil society and the financial intermediation of banks, with RBI and NABARD acting as more than willing midwives. </p><p> As the business potential of microfinance dawned on many, microfinance institutions (MFIs) took on the task of both the social and financial intermediation. Thus an alternate channel for microfinance arrived (somewhat belatedly by comparison to elsewhere in the world). This was second generation microfinance for India. Most of the MFIs adopted the Joint Liability Groups (JLGs) methodology, which is essentially the original Grameen peer group lending model, and standardisation became the new mantra for achieving rapid growth. Over the past 2-3 years, NBFC-MFIs operating under predominantly JLG-based methodology have emerged as a significant and rapidly growing force. </p><p> The burgeoning number of MFIs, and the relatively narrow focus of their products, has meant that intense competition has emerged, particularly in the southern states and in some limited areas of the east. This has provided microfinance borrowers with unprecedented access to credit. This has been a boon for them, but not without the concomitant vices of competition. Many of the larger MFIs are now responding to the demands of their commercial equity investors for very rapid expansion by adopting a “sales” driven approach for increasing outreach. The dash for growth has also seen several MFIs over-stretch their management capabilities and systems, resulting in significant portfolio problems. </p><p> To respond to the cut-throat competition MFIs are trying out different approaches that range from the desperate to the deliberate. The desperate measures have bordered on the unethical like “poaching” both credit officers and even groups from rival MFIs. Other more deliberate attempts have included offering individual lending (IL) products to their old clients. But the design of many MFIs&#39; IL product is little different from their group loans – except that the group guarantee is replaced by a single guarantor. Basic evaluation of the enterprise is usually performed, but the product is rarely customised to respond to cash flows, or even the financing needs, and reflects a pre-defined stepped loan schedule. And few MFIs invest in the skill sets required for a successful IL programme. </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/microsave_post_02.jpg class=alignleft> Given the saturation in a growing number of geographic markets, it is imperative for the MFIs to shift from a “product centric” to a “client centric” approach. The product-centric approach worked in uncompetitive markets with a huge demand-supply gap, and when the imperative was for rapid expansion. But as the number and outreach of MFIs has grown, supply is no more a constraint in many regions. Clients are in a position to pick-and-choose the MFI that offers them the most value. 3rd Generation MFIs will be quick to sense this “tectonic shift” in the dynamics of the highly competitive markets, and do everything they can to put the client back at the centre of their business. This focus will translate into a respect for client&#39;s time and dignity, and into making the entire spectrum of financial services for her livelihood available to her – a welcome prospect for both clients and those who believe in microfinance as a service for development and poverty eradication. </p><p><span  >第三代微型金融机构将付诸行动，深化参与的策略：</span> </p><ol><li> <span  >在向客户提供满足他们的金融需求-信贷全方位的金融服务套件，储蓄，汇款，保险等</span> </li><li> <span  >专注于为所有客户提供便利-使产品响应客户的需求，而不仅是该机构的。</span> </li><li> <span  >利用技术，特别是e-/m-banking以提高交易效率，降低成本。</span> </li><li> <span  >添加如“生活”的服务和教育，辅助服务/粮食安全服务，或什至可能的保健服务。</span> </li></ol><p> <span  >更多讯息请参阅<a href="http://bit.ly/M7rOW">http://bit.ly/M7rOW</a>和<a href="http://bit.ly/2Sihm">http://bit.ly/2Sihm</a></span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>印度储备银行（RBI）有一个既保持和移动小额支付严格规定的声誉。</strong></span> <span  > <strong>这些规章开始减弱，什么样的机遇和挑战</strong> ， <strong>你在地平线上看到？</strong></span> </p><p> <span  >印度储备银行（RBI）带出了银行业记者在2006年1月发出通告，使银行建立代理关系的基本金融服务的联合国库存的和没有银行分行根据本地区社会库存的部分附近。</span> <span  >另一个其后发出通告，限制记者不非营利性实体。</span> <span  >尽管监管机构施加的明显的局限性，企图试水也许，银行推出的金融包容性不足的地域重大举措。</span> <span  >大型公共部门银行的一些管理良好的外展和在不到两年的时间，超过100万客户更多的人&#39;倾斜&#39;。</span> <span  >不过，由银行和技术供应商，超过85％的客户自己承认的模式下，记者打开的“冬眠”。</span> <span  >这使银行在这个阶段，思想是，“是根据银行代理业务渠道的倡议主张抑或是企业的社会责任倡议？”迄今的迹象是，银行的结论是，根据现行规定，这是企业社会责任活动。</span> <span  >因此开立帐户，并报告给印度储备银行的交易，但不鼓励。</span> </p><p> <span  >工作组成立的审查根据体育维贾雅巴斯卡尔在8月18日，2009年，提交了报告银行业记者模型提出了一系列建议，其中许多是由博士D. Subbarao，总督，印度储备银行的批准第二季度货币政策审查2009-10年。</span> <span  >在审查，总督说：“根据小组的建议，建议：</span> </p><ul><li> <span  >让银行任命下列实体，除了那些已获准囊胚：（一）个人基拉那[小型零售] /医疗/公平的价格店铺的业主;（二）个别公共电话局（PCO）经营者;（三）代理小储蓄，印度政府计划/保险公司;（四）个人谁拥有的加油站;（五）退休教师;和（六）认可的运行良好的自助团体（自助团体）与银行工作人员;及</span> </li><li> <span  >让银行在其董事会收集就在一个透明的方式客户合理的服务费，批准通过公元前提供服务的政策。</span> <span  >这应该是清楚解释给客户。</span> </li></ul><p> <span  >微额是绝对相信，这些和监管制度的一些额外的放宽，印度可能会接近100％的覆盖范围在5-10年间的潜在联合国-满400亿美元的市场，这是一个巨大的商机机会。</span> <span  >三挑战依然存在：</span> </p><ol><li><span  >这项规定，在提供电子银行参与或米银行服务，是需要有在30千米分行（或15千米，在城市地区的潜在客户）/代理商-这在许多领域有效地限制了服务供应商的一些公共部门银行。</span> </li><li> <span  >限制谁可以作为代理人意味着银行在它们的组织/人员大量聚集的搜索挣扎。</span> <span  >在大多数国家，移动运营商网络的代理人或连锁超市，加油站或药店通常使用。</span> <span  >这些连锁店让银行招聘/训练和管理人员集体而非个人-后者是一个非常昂贵的。</span> </li><li> <span  >对于偏远地区，例如印度东部以北，它可能有必要对现行规定，要求所有的事务都被记录在银行的书籍在24小时内，会加入暂时搁置。</span> </li></ol><p> <span  >如果这些问题得到解决，为银行和其他金融机构利用的机会，技术的非凡-有国内汇款市场预计“Rs.26 ,000 - 40，000亿卢比”（见<a href="http://bit.ly/2jbYnj">http://bit.ly/2jbYnj）;</a>为各种保险服务的巨大潜在需求（如果他们得到适当的专为低收入市场）;当然，正如世界各地所示，存款动员潜力给予适当的产品和销售渠道是惊人的（见例如<a href="http://bit.ly/1rT0x0">http://bit.ly/1rT0 × 0）。</a></span> </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/microsave_post_01.jpg class=alignright> <span  > <strong>有关各方如何能够帮助？</strong></span> </p><p> <span  >作为监管环境变得更加有利的电子和移动银行，我们都需要共同努力，制定健全，服务于客户的产品和渠道，了解成本和收入的基本他们-从而使成功的商业模式的发展这为穷人创造真正的价值。</span> <span  >太多太多的e-/m-banking为穷人仍然言辞，但潜力是明确的-在理解的需要和穷人的行为更明确的重点，由银行真正承诺到农村，延伸服务深度可改变不只是地方性金融排斥，而且大部分发展面临的挑战当今世界。</span> </p><p> <span  > _______________________________________________</span> </p><p> <span  >格雷厄姆安赖特帮助设计和建立的微额方案，目的是印度目前项目主任。</span> <span  >格雷厄姆开创了市场很大的核心主导的微额使用的方法，特别是市场研究-对小额信贷工具。</span> <span  >他有两个五，在管理咨询，培训和审计经验的基础与在欧洲领先的会计事务所的发展经验，十年的职业生涯。</span> <span  >他是改革的特许会计师。</span> </p><p> <span  >格雷厄姆提供培训和技术援助的小额贷款机构在孟加拉国，印度，菲律宾和整个非洲的品种。</span> <span  >他帮助开发，测试和实施可持续的农村储蓄和信贷BURO联手计划，现在是一个有影响的孟加拉国小额信贷机构。</span> <span  >他提供长期的技术援助，以发展农村金融系统，采用自助“储蓄和贷款组”，与在菲律宾的偏远山区，以坚强的合作社。</span> <span  >他还参与了培训，系统设计，研究和评价捐助者通常字母汤。</span> </p><p> <span  >格雷厄姆已经撰写了14个培训包和25篇，包括题为“小额信贷系统：设计质量财政为穷人服务”（大学出版社有限公司，达卡和Zed书籍，伦敦和纽约，2000年）一书。</span> <span  >他还主持了贫穷者的工作和动员储蓄的产品开发组成员，在发展政策和管理，英国曼彻斯特大学研究所助理研究员。</span> </p></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-316> <span  > <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/11/mobile-money-and-conflict/" rel=bookmark title="永久链接到移动货币与冲突">移动货币与冲突</a></span> </h3> <span  > <small>张贴在<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">博客</a> 11月<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">员额</a> 18日，由主机2009 - <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/11/mobile-money-and-conflict/#respond" title="评论流动货币和冲突">成为第一位评论</a></small></span> <div class=entry><p><span  >移动银行业务的潜力，跨越现有的主流是国家的银行显然无法获得与传统的银行和金融服务的庞大的人口数量。</span> <span  >在这种情况下，手机银行，简化现有的金融交易，这可能需要几个月的时间和成本的价值交换的比例过高。</span> <span  >相反，即时，低成本的资金转移，使这些价格适中，甚至允许交易，否则将是不切实际的。</span> <span  >另一项功能，它可以提供移动银行，但是，很容易组这些简化交易，均可能不会发生之前，而不是因为他们买不起或不切实际的交易，但由于冲突和被迫迁移。</span> </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/crisis_post_1.jpg class=alignleft> <span  >其中有重大来自达尔富尔，巴勒斯坦，伊拉克，西撒哈拉被迫移民的个人经验，和索马里，我听到第一手的经济孤立的是其他国家削减对全球金融交易的依赖超过普通市民的反感，甚至是无法获得银行。</span> <span  >这些冲突地区可能缺乏，不仅传统的银行基础设施，甚至有时，获得取决于金融工具在经济上最孤立的国家行动。</span> <span  >在这种情况下，当现金可能不可用或不可靠的（由于恶性通货膨胀，或假冒）和其他资产没有足够的流动资金将受保护的，面对冲突运输，通信的必要性仍然是最重要，和移动电话基础设施继续得到保持，并提供移动银行业务的基础设施。</span> <span  >即使在达尔富尔，苏丹政府将削减对叛军的攻势，在所有移动电话服务，卫星电话，可以在最偏远地区用于转移信贷和维持通讯线路。</span> <span  >同样，在索马里，广泛的暴力和无政府状态，抵消了大部分的主流金融机构的信心，移动电话网络之间的Africa1更好的措施，和经济学家声称，从索马里移动电话：“呼吁普遍较便宜和更清晰来自非洲的其他地方。“2调用</span> </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/crisis_post_2.jpg class=alignright> <span  >我们可以看到这种潜力实际上是被利用的一点，尽管是非正式的，在伊拉克，其中“不愿冒险通过访问银行他们的生活，许多[伊拉克电话]用户转让有关的序列号通过相互钱信贷指控，如礼品券。“3的安全性，流动性和discreetness独特结合刮刮卡允许移动信贷执行一个不能被任何传统的金融工具替代的作用，无论时间尺度或成本。</span> <span  >在承认伊拉克社区的意义，“联合国说，它计划推出以同样的方式援助伊拉克难民在叙利亚。”4这种体制转向移动金融交易强调了在冲突情况下的流动货币独特的地方，因为没有其他手段，实在方便。</span> <span  >一位美国政府实习描述了与移动的钱支付伊拉克士兵一个试点项目，因为其中四分之一休假在任何时候，因为他们得不到他们的pay.5如果连这些大官僚机构找到一种方法，纳入其结构，移动多少钱可能有潜在的敏捷和灵活的地方非政府组织的工作在地面上。</span> </p><p>The need for mobile financial transactions in countries from Iraq to Mauritania is not limited to situations of crisis, conflict and forced migration. However the ingenuity and resilience of some of the populations in these countries in the face of these challenges is teaching us how mobile money can solve financial problems that previously could not be addressed at all. In working with FrontlineSMS:Credit as the regional coordinator for the Middle East and North Africa region, I am eager to learn more about the different ways that mobile phone users in these regions are leveraging technology to make a difference in times of conflict and peace. </p><p><img class=alignleft src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/team_joel.jpg /><br /> <em>This post was contributed by Joel Mitchell, North Africa &amp; Middle East Regional Coordinator for FrontlineSMS:Credit.</em> </p><p> To contact Joel, email <a href=mailto:joel@credit.frontlinesms.com>joel@credit.frontlinesms.com</a> or follow him on Twitter at <a href="http://twitter.com/jdmitchjoel"target=_blank>@jdmitchjoel</a> . </p><h5> <span  > ____________________</span> <br /> <span  > 1。</span> Ford, Nowrasteh, Powell; 2006. “Somalia After State Collapse: Chaos or Improvement?” Independent Institute Working Paper Number 64. November 30, 2006. Oakland, CA. http://www.independent.org. <br /> <span  > 2。</span> Economist Editors. “Mobile Phones” The Economist. December 20-24, 2005. <br /> <span  > 3。</span> Economist Editors. “Iraq&#39;s Mobile Phone Revolution: Better than Freedom?” The Economist. November 14-20, 2009. <br /> <span  > 4。</span> Op. Cit. <br /> 5. <a href="http://a517dogg.blogspot.com/2007/07/mobile-banking-and-poverty-part-1.html"target=_blank>http://a517dogg.blogspot.com/2007/07/mobile-banking-and-poverty-part-1.html</a> </h5></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-281> <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/11/our-own-line-in-the-sand/" rel=bookmark title="Permanent Link to Our own line in the sand">Our own line in the sand</a> </h3> <small>Posted in <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">Blog posts</a> on November 8th, 2009  by Ben Lyon – <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/11/our-own-line-in-the-sand/#comments" title="Comment on Our own line in the sand">2 Comments</a></small> <div class=entry><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/line_in_the_sand.jpg align=left class=alignleft> In response to a lively debate on “the cloud” and “appropriate technology”, Ken Banks of <a href="http://www.kiwanja.net/"trget=_blank>kiwanja.net</a> recently wrote a blog post titled “Our &#39;social mobile&#39; line in the sand”. The purpose of the post was to articulate where FrontlineSMS stands with regard to five key mobile tools for development. In the spirit of openness and precision, we felt it necessary to write a similar post to outline where FrontlineSMS and FrontlineSMS:Credit are both similar and different. </p><p> First, to echo Ken, our primary goal is to provide the end user with a tool that is appropriate and intuitive. Although the levels of sophistication in the mobile space vary, especially when it comes to mobile payments and finance, our aim is to construct a tool that utilizes as many pre-existing channels and competencies as possible. Why reinvent the wheel? </p><p> <span  > <strong>1。</strong></span> <strong>Who is your target audience?</strong> </p><p> Our ideal target audience is Tier 3 and Tier 4 microfinance institutions (MFIs) whose clients have access to some form of mobile payment system. FrontlineSMS:Credit may also benefit institutions that need to send mobile payments en masse. Payroll, compensation, crisis relief, and incentive-based programs are good examples of the latter. </p><p> In the long run, we plan to provide a comparable tool to Tier 1 and Tier 2 MFIs. Doing so, however, will require a more sophisticated, web-based approach and is therefore not a current priority. Further, Tier 3 and Tier 4 MFIs, which typically spring from and align themselves with grassroots needs, are likely to have greater access to rural populations that are un- or under-served in the status quo. </p><p> <span  > <strong>2。</strong></span> <strong>What is your position on scaling?</strong> </p><p> We support scaling and centralization as long as it&#39;s user-driven and practical. Nevertheless, we are hesitant to promote centralized approaches where regulatory and infrastructural ecosystems are weak or ill-defined. To put it simply, it would be imprudent to subject the finances of the unbanked poor to a single point of failure. </p><p> With horizontal scaling, which we prefer, risk is evenly spread across implementing institutions. Any failure is therefore isolated to a particular hub instead of the system as a whole. </p><p> <span  > <strong>3。</strong></span> <strong>How does it replicate and grow?</strong> </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/line_in_the_sand_2.jpg class=alignright> Like FrontlineSMS and FrontlineSMS:Medic, we are driven by “pull” from interested organizations. 100% of our upcoming pilot and beta partners, for instance, initiated contact to collaborate. As a result of time saved from not seeking partners, we can commit the majority of our efforts to getting feedback from potential users and adjusting our designs accordingly. The FrontlineSMS:Credit team is large and geographically scattered for precisely this reason. </p><p> <span  > <strong>4。</strong></span> <strong>What is your position on open sourcing?</strong> </p><p> We consider open sourcing essential for improvement and continued innovation. Unlike FrontlineSMS, however, we will need to closely monitor and scrutinize changes to the source code in order to protect end users from fraud (eg a developer could build a back door into the system to access financial data and PIN numbers). Since economic shocks at the bottom of the pyramid can be a matter of life or death, we will have to ensure that any modifications to the code are both secure and made in good faith. </p><p> <span  > <strong>5。</strong></span> <strong>Does access to the Internet matter?</strong> </p><p> No.  By providing the data bridge necessary to take full advantage of mobile payment systems, MFIs will be able to provide a range of financial services via the cellular network. Although an internet connection will allow MFIs to backup user data (which could also be achieved with a simple thumb drive), one won&#39;t be necessary for FrontlineSMS:Credit to function. </p><p> <strong>Note:</strong> <em>FrontlineSMS:Credit is currently under development and will be available for free download this Spring. It is being designed to function as middleware that will enable any mobile payment system and any management information system (MIS) to communicate in real time. As a result, implementing MFIs will be able to distribute loans, receive repayments and generate robust auditing trails and client credit histories directly from their MIS.</em> </p></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-222> <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/10/arc-finance-highlights-our-raison-detre/" rel=bookmark title="Permanent Link to Arc Finance Highlights our Raison D&#8217;être">Arc Finance Highlights our Raison D&#39;être</a> </h3> <small>Posted in <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">Blog posts</a> on October 27th, 2009  by host – <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/10/arc-finance-highlights-our-raison-detre/#comments" title="Comment on Arc Finance Highlights our Raison D&#8217;être">4 Comments</a></small> <div class=entry><p> <a href="http://www.arcfinance.org/"target=_blank><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/arc_logo.jpg alt=arc_logo title="arc_logo" width=108 height=106 class="alignleft size-full wp-image-225" border=0 /></a> <em>The nonprofit, Arc Finance, is looking into ways to expand access to financing for modern energy, clean water, and other basic needs globally, and is interested to see how mobile payment systems are being used currently to make payments/remittances possible in rural settings. In the email below, Mike MacHarg of Arc Finance highlights some of the issues facing one NGO making mobile payments to farmers in Kenya.</em> </p><p> Dear XXXX, </p><p> Got some interesting feedback from the group XXXX, that uses Safaricom&#39;s MPesa system to pay its tree farmers (they pay farmers quarterly in Kenya, India and Tanzania for tree planting – through funds raised on the voluntary carbon market). </p><p> <span  > <strong>它是如何工作：</strong></span> </p><p> XXXX has small groups of 8-12 farmers each. XXXX makes quarterly payments to the small group, to a single Safaricom (in Kenya) SIM card held by the group. There is a checks and balance system built in, as at least three farmers from the small group have to show up at the meeting when the transfer is made, and one has the SIM card, another the PIN number for MPesa collection, and a third has the voucher for the payment (voucher is issued beforehand when it is confirmed the trees were actually planted?). </p><p> <strong>Issues and challenges:</strong> </p><p><a href="http://www.safaricom.co.ke/index.php?id=745"target=_blank><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/safaricom.jpg alt=safaricom title="Safaricom公司" width=250 height=230 class="alignright size-full wp-image-229" border=0 /></a> <span  > 1）交易费用相对较高的农民支付小额款项。</span> One issue has been that the transfer fees within Safaricom/MPesa are high relative to the small payments being made to the group. Either XXXX has to absorb that cost, or pass it onto the farmers. In Safaricom&#39;s case, it does not pay to make very small payments. </p><p> 2) SIM card deactivation over time: In the small group model, the SIM card is only used quarterly by the group for the money transfer, and for no other purpose. Unfortunately, Safaricom deactivates SIM cards that are dormant for long periods (like 3mo) – so XXXX has faced the issue of having to reactivate all of their small group SIM cards prior to each money transfer. Causes major delay in transfer, and can cause farmer payment meetings to take up to 6 hours. </p><p> Deactivation may be different with different vendors (MTN, Orange), but something to consider. XXXX is trying to determine other ways to keep cards active, such as sending a negligible amount of airtime, say 1 Ksh (there is no fee for transferring air time) – so that the SIMs stay active. </p><p> 3) SIM card registration: this may play into the regulatory environments for mobile payment systems, but XXXX has recently found out that it is “illegal” to register the SIM cards to small groups – and not to an actual business or individual. This probably has to do with “know your customer” regulations that have to do with banking – that are being carried over to mobile money transfer operations. Another thing to consider if you use the small group model. </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/mpesa_news_main.jpg alt=mpesa_news_main title="mpesa_news_main" width=285 height=189 class="alignleft size-full wp-image-234" /> 4) Transfer time: XXXX brings its small groups together on a certain day, and meets with them physically to do the mobile money transfer. While you might think it would be easier to just pay out cash in this setting – there is enough of a security issue that the mobile payments still make more sense. But transfers are not often instantaneous – and intermittent cell phone connections in rural areas can drag out the transfer process for up to 3-4 hours, as each transfer has to be uploaded to MPesa, and then farmers will wait to verify the payment has indeed made it back to their SIM card. </p><p> 5) SIM credit limits: XXXX has to use up to 4 of their own SIM cards to make the payments from, since there are limits (with Safaricom) as to how much credit any individual SIM card can hold at one time. So to make $400 in payments, XXXX might use four SIM cards that have a limit of $100 each. </p><p> 6) Record keeping: To date, Safaricom has been resistant to providing XXXX with records of their individual transfers to each of the small group&#39;s SIM cards. Obviously valuable data for XXXX to have to keep track of payments to farmers, and for now they are reliant on paper based records to keep track of data that Safaricom is already keeping. Safaricom has said that they are looking into making such data available, but has resisted in helping XXXX to date (as it sees no great profit incentive to supply such data). </p><p> <em>Individual and organization names have been redacted for privacy purposes. The email author, Mike MacHarg, is available for comment and can be reached at <br /> <a href=mailto:mike.macharg@gmail.com>mike.macharg “AT” gmail.com</a> .</em> </p></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-208> <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/10/leveraging-technology-for-microfinance/" rel=bookmark title="Permanent Link to Leveraging Technology for Microfinance">Leveraging Technology for Microfinance</a> </h3> <small>Posted in <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">Blog posts</a> on October 19th, 2009  by host – <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/10/leveraging-technology-for-microfinance/#respond" title="Comment on Leveraging Technology for Microfinance">Be the first to comment</a></small> <div class=entry><p> The microfinance sector has arrived at a fork in the road. For a long while it has sought to raise awareness and publicity for the plight of the poor and for funding of its operations. </p><p>With the award of the Nobel Peace Prize in 2006 to Prof Muhammad Yunus of the <a href="http://www.grameen-info.org/"target=_blank>Grameen Bank</a> , the sector has been basking in its glow and has been able to attract a lot of attention and funding for the very good work that it does. </p><p> And this glow has decreased considerably in the past year due to the global economic downturn. MFI&#39;s both big and small have been struggling due to lack of funding and dearth of funding sources. The issue of operational inefficiencies, high operating costs at MFI&#39;s big and small has heightened. The MFI&#39;s customers are also hurting from higher energy, fuel, and food costs. That&#39;s the macro picture. </p><p> MFI&#39;s have limited set of choices to make to improve their financial plight / viability: </p><ol><li> To grow and scale their operations – adding new customers more rapidly and retaining existing ones, </li><li> To increase the interest rates and fees that they charge customers – which allows them to generate more revenue and would help improve their financial bottom-line, ie to be more profitable, </li><li> To reduce customer and staffing “churn”, ie to increase retention rates of existing customers, and of their staff, </li><li> To lower their operating costs </li></ol><p> Confronted with these choices, all MFI&#39;s want to grow and scale their operations. However given the limited funding available, social investors and capital markets only target those MFI&#39;s that are profitable and well managed. And even these MFI&#39;s do not get all of the funding that they may want or desire. </p><p> The other option is to increase rates and fees. With the banks also hurting, they are also seeking other sources for customer growth, and are moving downstream to target customers that have been the domain of MFI&#39;s. The competitive landscape has changed in some geographies and/or is changing in others. If MFI&#39;s were to adopt this option they would do so at their own peril. Customers would vote with their feet and run to another MFI or bank that offers lower rates and fees. </p><p> Most MFI&#39;s have very high “churn” rates of their customers, ie they lose customers after being with them for one loan cycle. And coupled with this they lose lot of staff which means they are constantly losing operational and customer knowledge. </p><p> This then brings us to the last option, to lower operating costs. <span  >如何？</span> MFI&#39;s need to focus and work on the low-hanging fruit to try and reduce their costs. First by adopting policies and practices (eg to provide on-going training on policies, products, processes, and customer service) to retain their “good” performing staff, and to improve customer retention (ie to adopt practices that makes the customer not want to go elsewhere – and customers even these ones do not all move because of price). Secondly, to improve,  streamline and automate their operational processes, to ensure that these processes are properly documented and maintained, and to provide on-going training on these processes to their staff. Most MFI&#39;s, big and small, pay little attention to effectively managing their operational practices and processes. </p><p> This is where we, the technology solutions and service providers, can play a critical role to help MFI&#39;s not just lower their operating costs but can also help them to scale their operations and retain customers. </p><p> The bulk of the MFI&#39;s front-end processes are manual, and fraught with errors, ie loan officers (LOs) use pen &amp; paper to collect customer information, and then this “hieroglyphics” is given to a person in the branch to enter into a system or an Excel spreadsheet; LOs again use pen &amp; paper to track and manage customer repayments, etc … There is little or no credit scoring or credit decisioning capability available to the LO. The time it takes from the initial conversation with the customer to being approved for a loan to loan disbursement is too long. There is little or no info captured on micro businesses in the 2 mile, 5 mile, 10 mile radius of a specfic village or market – such info would be useful to predict the viability of the customer&#39;s business when it comes to making a loan approve or decline decision rather than leaving it to the gut or experience of the LO. </p><p> At the end of the day, MFI&#39;s performance comes down to what their PAR (portfolio at risk) is at day 30, 60, 90, etc. Proactive management of loan repayments is a critical element to keeping PAR low. By providing hand-held or mobile solutions to MFI&#39;s to give to their LO&#39;s that can help manage and track “like” businesses in the area, customer repayment history, being able to print receipts, etc can significantly assist to not just improve PAR but also to help streamline and improve their processes. </p><p> We within the technology sector, and especially at FrontlineSMS:Credit, have a wonderful opportunity to play a significant and a meaningful role to help ease some of the cost burdens faced by MFI&#39;s. I am looking forward to learn more about FrontlineSMS:Credit and to work with the team to help shape its roadmap. </p><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-184" title="hillmer_reyes" src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/team_jiten.jpg alt=team_jiten width=128 height=128 /> <em>Jiten Patel is the Director of Product Development for FrontlineSMS:Credit. He has experience working for both for-profits and non-profits and most recently served as Chief Information Officer of <a href="http://www.villagebanking.org/"target=_blank>FINCA International</a> .</em> To contact Jiten, email <a href=mailto:jiten@credit.frontlinesms.com>Jiten@credit.frontlinesms.com</a> or follow him on Twitter at <a href="http://twitter.com/nomadic_cio"target=_blank>@nomadic_cio</a> . </p></div></div><div class=navigation><div class=alignleft> <span  > <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/page/2/" >«旧条目</a></span> </div><div class=alignright></div></div></div><div id=sidebar><ul><li id=rssfeeds><table border=0><tr><td> <span  > <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/feed/">订阅</a></span> </td><td></td><td>
